l that surrounded the small courtyard, the distinctive tramp of studded boots signaled the patrol of the night watch.  It was an unusually quiet evening in East Freeport, and the hushed surf of the distant sea could be heard.  <br>
<br>
The tang of the salt air was pleasant and it brought to Dalain’s mind other times.  Past instances where he sat by the sea.  Memories of long ago when he would sit by the sea with his love.  He had confessed his feelings for her in the spray of the salt sea.  He was such a fumbling young fool in love then.  Inexperienced in the ways of love in spite of his advanced years…  Ay… he was feeling his age this night.  He was glad it was summer.  The damp sea air in winter sometimes reminded his body of every major battle and hurts received even though they had been long healed.  Here he was… a grown daughter at his feet...  a love long lost… Elves were so long-lived, they seemed immortal to humans.  He wondered how Arawyne looked.  Probably as fresh and beautiful as the day they met…  <br>
<br>
He was lost in his memories when his daughter spoke, asking a question.<br>
<br>
~~<br>
<br>
Delaine was lying on the grass beside the rough-hewn bench in her foster-parents’ yard, gazing up at the stars.  Her Da was having a well-deserved drink at the local pub, and her Ma was inside the house doing something.  Her birth-father sat on the bench, seemingly lost in thought.  She wondered what he was thinking about.  She had easily grown to respect and love him, and she was glad that her Da and Ma took to him and he to they.  He often came to dinner with them when he was in town, enjoying their simple repasts, praising her Ma on her cooking, always bringing a bottle of wine or some sweet.  She had not known until he showed her his jeweler’s mark on her own diamond band, that her mother had given her, that he was a jeweler.  <br>
<br>
Her birth-father was an interesting and accomplished man.  She wondered again what he had done.  The act that her birth-mother had called “stupid” that had provoked her so she struck out in return and broke them up so irrevocably.  Her mother had never offered the information and she had never dared ask.  But her father… that was a different matter.  So she asked.<br>
<br>
“Father?”<br>
<br>
Pulled out of his reverie, Dalain turned.<br>
<br>
“Yes, Delaine?”<br>
<br>
“Whatcha do that made mother so mad that she made you duel her?”<br>
<br>
Dalain thought a while before answering and looked at his daughter.  Delaine looked back at him steadfastly, her eyes bright and questioning.<br>
<br>
It was all ancient history.  Dalain thought, and there was little need to go into the old hurts and fears, but perhaps she deserved an answer of some sort.  Distilling all the past into the deed, he replied.<br>
<br>
“I was giving her up.”<br>
<br>
“Why were you giving her up?”<br>
<br>
“Because I thought she deserved better.”<br>
<br>
Delaine looked back up at the starry night.<br>
<br>
“Mother was right… That was stupid.”<br>
<br>
“Thank you.”<br>
<br>
Dalain smiled wryly.<br>
<br>
“You’re welcome.”<br>
<br>
Silence reigned between them.  Delaine was thinking hard.  She wondered if she had offended her father.  Da did always say she had too big a mouth sometimes and needed to start her brain before she started her mouth.<br>
<br>
She pondered how she was going to ask the next question.  Ahhh…<br>
<br>
“That was stupid, father, because… how could mother have done better than you?”<br>
<br>
Dalain smiled, recognizing his daughter’s attempt at diplomacy.<br>
<br>
“Sometimes people in love do silly things.  I thought that I was doing the best by her.”<br>
<br>
“Mmmmph…”<br>
<br>
Delaine was sitting up now, hugging her knees and Dalain reached over and ruffled her hair.<br>
<br>
“Maybe one day you will fall in love and understand a little.  It was not quite that simple, Lainie.  Many things were involved, but basically, I loved your mother, but saw her little and could not give her the attention she deserved.  So I thought I was doing the right thing.”<br>
<br>
“Mmmmph…” <br>
<br>
Delaine grunted, and then was silent for a space of time before she spoke again.<br>
<br>
“You think you’d ever get together again?”<br>
<br>
Dalain sighed.  So that was what it was about.<br>
<br>
“No.”<br>
<br>
“Why not?”<br>
<br>
Dalain shrugged.<br>
<br>
“She doesn’t love me anymore.  She didn’t even tell me that she had you... that we had you.”<br>
<br>
Delaine was thinking hard.  That was what mother had said too.  That father did not love her anymore…<br>
<br>
“Do you love her still?”<br>
<br>
Dalain raised an expressive eyebrow.<br>
<br>
“What’s this, Lainie?  Twenty questions?  This was all a long time ago.”<br>
<br>
“Mmmmmph…”<br>
<br>
“And what is that supposed to mean, young lady?”<br>
<br>
“Just thinking, Father.”<br>
<br>
“About?”<br>
<br>
Delaine rose to her feet and hugged her birth father tight.<br>
<br>
“You and mother, and Gramma, and Da and Ma… and how lucky I am to have all of you.”<br>
<br>
Dalain smiled and hugged his daughter back.<br>
<br>
“I’m lucky too.  Lucky to have you, lucky that you found me.”<br>
