<br>
“Stop pacing, dear.”<br>
<br>
Cassandra murmured as Delaine passed her chair again.<br>
<br>
“Yes, Gramma.”<br>
<br>
Delaine continued pacing.  Cassandra clucked her tongue.<br>
<br>
“Sit.”<br>
<br>
Delaine pulled out a chair and sat, drumming her fingers on the table.<br>
<br>
Arawyne frowned at her daughter.<br>
<br>
“What is the matter, Delaine?”<br>
<br>
She jumped up again, but was saved from having to answering by her grandmother.<br>
<br>
“I am having a visitor, Arawyne.  Delaine is a little excited, I think.”<br>
<br>
“Oh?”<br>
<br>
Arawyne raised an eyebrow.  She did not like her mother’s expression.  She looked like the cat that had found sweet cream unattended.  In fact… her mother had the same expression when she was presenting marriage minded candidates to her years ago.  Scheming little wench!<br>
<br>
Cassandra nodded.<br>
<br>
“Aye.  Perhaps I should say that Delaine and I are having a visitor to tea.”<br>
<br>
Arawyne frowned.<br>
<br>
“Anyone I know?”<br>
<br>
Cassandra nodded again.<br>
<br>
Arawyne glared at her mother.  Cassandra was playing games.  But over the years, she had learned to either play or gracefully allow her mother her schemes, and it took much less energy to simply allow her mother her schemes.<br>
<br>
“Well you should have told me.  I would have baked more muffins or perhaps cake.”<br>
<br>
Cassandra smiled.<br>
<br>
“There is plenty of that.  But perhaps a little more tea?  I hear the kettle.  Use the larger tea pot.”<br>
<br>
“I’ll do it, Gramma.”<br>
<br>
Delaine volunteered, and escaped into the kitchen.<br>
<br>
~~~~<br>
<br>
Dalain walked through Felwithe, following the instructions his daughter had given him.  He made a wide berth around the paladin’s guild.  He was not sure of his welcome there since that little incident where his guild had trampled some rose bushes in Tunare’s garden, but did not want trouble.<br>
<br>
He was a little nervous and wondered again how he had let his daughter talk him into this.  How did one act when meeting one’s daughter’s grandmother?  What would he say to her?<br>
<br>
“Hi there.  Yeah.  I’m the one that knocked up your daughter.  But I didn’t know.  Really!”<br>
<br>
He grinned.  He was being foolish now.  He had met Cassandra Goldenmoon once before.  At a conclave in Freeport over the threat of Lanys T’val, the daughter of Innoruuk.  She was a stately elf.  Calm and collected.  Suuuuure… he would say something like that to her.  Maybe it would rattle her.  Then again, maybe he would just look foolish.<br>
<br>
He arrived at his destination and double-checked the directions on the many-times folded parchment again.  Taking a deep breath, he knocked on the door and stood back.  Then the door opened and he forgot to breathe.<br>
<br>
~~<br>
<br>
Arawyne stood at the knocks on her mother’s door.<br>
<br>
“I’ll get it mother.”<br>
<br>
“Thank you dear.  Bring him to the parlor.  I’m sure Delaine will have tea ready.”<br>
<br>
“Yes, mother.”<br>
<br>
She opened the door and stared at their visitor, her greeting frozen in her throat.  If she had been asked, the last person she would have guessed would have would have been he that stood in front of her now.<br>
<br>
~~~<br>
<br>
Dalain stared at Arawyne, his heart constricting in him as the smile left her face.<br>
<br>
“Arawyne.”<br>
<br>
“Dalain.”<br>
<br>
They stood, wrapped in time, staring at each other until Cassandra took the door from her daughter and opened it wide.<br>
<br>
“Dalain!  Welcome!”<br>
<br>
Taking him by the arm, she ushered him past her daughter.  Dalain’s eyes stayed on Arawyne until he passed her and perforce had to turn his attention to Cassandra.  Before he could speak, Delaine came out of the kitchen with a laden tray.<br>
<br>
“Father!  You came!”<br>
<br>
Her voice was joyful yet relieved, and he smiled.<br>
<br>
“Of course I did.”<br>
<br>
Arawyne closed the front door slowly as all three entered the parlor, and contemplated making her escape.  She didn’t seem needed.  Then her mother’s head popped out from the parlor.<br>
<br>
“Tea is poured, Arawyne.  Come.”<br>
<br>
Mother’s royal command.  She thought wryly and walked slowly to the parlor.<br>
<br>
