<br>
“I think mother just threw something at father.”<br>
<br>
“I hope it’s that hideous vase your grandfather’s aunt gave me.”<br>
<br>
Delaine grabbed her hair and whirled around to face her grandmother.<br>
<br>
“Ahhh!  How can you be so calm?”<br>
<br>
Cassandra smiled and nodded at the stool in front of her.<br>
<br>
“Come sit down, dear.”<br>
<br>
Delaine grabbed the stool and sat, propping her elbows on the table and her head in her hands.<br>
<br>
“Maybe this was one of my stupider ideas.”<br>
<br>
Cassandra laughed.<br>
<br>
“Actually, I thought it was a marvelous idea.”<br>
<br>
Delaine blinked.<br>
<br>
“You did?”<br>
<br>
“Aye.”<br>
<br>
“Why?”<br>
<br>
“Because they still love each other.”<br>
<br>
Delaine blinked again and winced as the sound of more breaking glass reached their ears again.<br>
<br>
“She just threw something else.”<br>
<br>
“I put the good vases away this morning, dear.”<br>
<br>
“How did you know?  How do you know?”<br>
<br>
Cassandra winked at her granddaughter and crossed her eyes.<br>
<br>
“Grandmother Cassandra knows all.  Sees all.”<br>
<br>
Delaine laughed.<br>
<br>
“Oh!  The witch woman persona!  How well you do it too!”<br>
<br>
Cassandra laughed with her granddaughter.<br>
<br>
“No, Gramma.  Tell me!  How did you know?”<br>
<br>
Cassandra smiled.<br>
<br>
“That your mother would throw things?”<br>
<br>
“No, Gramma, I mean… well, that too.”<br>
<br>
She laughed.<br>
<br>
“As if you don’t know your mother’s temper by now.”<br>
<br>
“I didn’t think she would throw things!  But Gramma, I mean… how do you know they still love each other?”<br>
<br>
“The way they looked at each other when one thought the other was not looking at them.  The longing in her eyes, the hunger in his perhaps?”<br>
<br>
Cassandra’s eyes twinkled.<br>
<br>
“Oh.”<br>
<br>
Delaine digested that piece of information.<br>
<br>
“You saw all that just over tea and cake?”<br>
<br>
“You grandmother has lived a long life, child, and is a seer to boot.  I’ve learned a lot about the nature of humans and elves.”<br>
<br>
Delaine nodded.<br>
<br>
“Do you think they will make up?”<br>
<br>
Cassandra smiled and picked up her teacup again, sipping from it while Delaine watched impatiently.<br>
<br>
“Yes, child.  I think they will.”<br>
<br>
“But mother’s yelling and throwing things!”<br>
<br>
Cassandra nodded again.<br>
<br>
“That is your mother’s nature.”<br>
<br>
“But… but…”<br>
<br>
Cassandra laughed.<br>
<br>
“Trust in your father, dear.  Your father and your mother were lovers for many years.  I’m sure he remembers how to handle your mother and her temper tantrums.”<br>
<br>
She reminisced.<br>
<br>
“I was first surprised that it lasted that long, then resigned that your mother would not be marrying a high-elf and continuing our line.”<br>
<br>
Another crash reached Delaine’s ears and she winced.<br>
<br>
“Are you sure, Gramma?”<br>
<br>
Her grandmother nodded and set her to the task of returning jars of herbs to their proper places on her shelves.  The chore done, Delaine sat with her Grandmother again, shooting glances at the parlor door anxiously.  Suddenly realizing that she had not heard anything else smash for a while, Delaine jumped up from the stool and ran to the parlor once more, pressing her ear to the door.  She frowned.<br>
<br>
“I can’t hear anything now.”<br>
<br>
Cassandra smiled and nodded.<br>
<br>
“Come away dear.”<br>
<br>
“But, I can’t hear anything!”<br>
<br>
Cassandra laughed.<br>
<br>
“Aye.  If your father is smart, he is kissing her to shut her up, and that will be that.”<br>
<br>
“Oh.”<br>
<br>
She opened the door a crack and peeked in.<br>
<br>
“Delaine!”<br>
<br>
Cassandra hissed her granddaughter’s name and set the herbs down.<br>
<br>
“Come away from there!”<br>
<br>
Delaine shut the door hurriedly and scurried over to her Grandmother’s side.  Her face was red with embarrassment.<br>
<br>
“Gramma!  They are… Father is…  Uhhh… Father… they are…”<br>
<br>
It was all Cassandra could do not to laugh at her granddaughter.  Wrapping a hand around her upper arm, she hauled her out of the house.<br>
<br>
“Time for you and I to take a walk.”<br>
